<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910618-0165</DOCNO><DOCID>910618-0165.</DOCID><HL>   Litton Industries   To Phase Down   One of Its Divisions   ----   By Earl C. Gottschalk Jr.   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><CO>   LIT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Litton Industries Inc. said itplans to phase down the operations of its IntegratedAutomation division in the near future because of a worseningoutlook for the division's software-based systems.   As a result, the diversified electronics concern said itwill take an after-tax charge of $100 million, or $4.50 ashare, against earnings for its fiscal fourth quarter endingJuly 31.</LP><TEXT>   For the first nine months, Litton had net income of $121.9million, or $5.53 a share, on sales of $3.84 billion. Littondeclined to project earnings for the quarter or the year.   The Integrated Automation division provides software-basedsystems for document imaging, inspection and process control.The division had fiscal 1990 revenue of about $50 million.It's part of Litton's Industrial Automation Group, which hadfiscal 1990 revenue of $728 million.   A Litton spokesman said 190 people are employed in theIntegrated Automation division, most of them in Alameda,Calif., and it wasn't clear how many of them would be laidoff, or how soon. &quot;We have contracts to be completed andadjustments to make,&quot; the spokesman said.   Alton J. Brann, Litton president, said that the company isclosing down the inspection and process control productlines, &quot;whose performance turned out to be disappointing.&quot;The software systems are used for optical scanning ofmaterial passing through continuous flow systems.   The remaining document imaging system business has a muchnarrower scope, serving a smaller market with limited growthopportunities, Mr. Brann said.   The recession has accelerated the division's problems,which won't substantially reverse, once the economy turns, hesaid. He said the outlook and performance in the rest of thecompany's continuing industrial automation business isimproving.</TEXT></DOC>